      <h2>Extended email marketing playbook for digital product shops</h2>
      <p>This section is the retention magazine view of digital product shops: not which app has the prettiest templates, but which inbox moments actually move repeat purchase when delivery, onboarding, cross-sells, and low-inventory constraints dominate operations.</p>
      <p>Start with consent archaeology. Map every popup, checkout, footer, SMS keyword, and partner import that feeds email. digital product shops often fail when giveaway subscribers receive the same welcome as high-intent product-page signups.</p>
      <p>Week-one deliverable: welcome segmented by source with suppressions for existing customers, recent purchasers, and employees. If your current tool cannot branch on signup source, that is the selection constraint — not missing AI copy features.</p>
      <p>Week-two deliverable: one recovery flow with inventory checks and discount caps documented. digital product shops lose margin when cart recovery treats a $35 accessory and a $350 bundle identically.</p>
      <p>Week-three deliverable: post-purchase education tied to immediate delivery; onboarding critical; cross-sell within 7 days. The email should reduce support tickets and set up the next purchase — not only ask for a review on day one.</p>
      <p>Week-four deliverable: replenishment or winback with VIP exclusions. Track Activation rate post-purchase and Cross-sell within 14 days against Shopify net sales, not only ESP attribution.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first in our digital product shops shortlist because agent-first playbooks compress those four weeks for lean teams. Klaviyo wins when someone owns predictive segments weekly. Omnisend wins when SMS must ship beside email immediately.</p>
      <p>Pricing discipline: model 90-day sends, not 90-day profiles. digital product shops with wide lists and narrow engagement punish per-contact billing — pay-per-email alternatives reward pruning and targeting.</p>
      <p>Sale-week governance: document which flows pause when site-wide promos run. Collision between welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and campaign blasts is the silent LTV killer for digital product shops.</p>
      <p>Deliverability preflight before peak season: SPF, DKIM, DMARC alignment, popup-offer match, sunset policies for 180-day inactives, and seedlist tests across Gmail and Apple Mail.</p>
      <p>When leaving a legacy sender, export consent timestamps and parallel-run critical flows two weeks. Attribution debates slow adoption more than template rebuilds.</p>
      <p>Final operator rule for digital product shops: email should feel like the store remembering the customer — product context, timing respect, and margin honesty. Pick the app your team will tune every Monday.</p>
      <p>Use the comparison hub when torn between two finalists — workflow tests beat feature matrices. Use use-case playbooks for trigger, timing, and exclusion detail on welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback.</p>
      <p>If you only fix one thing this quarter for digital product shops, fix suppression logic. Recent buyers, VIPs, wholesale accounts, and gift purchasers should not receive stranger-discount language — that single change often lifts placement and LTV more than a new template pack.</p>
